fety ladder, modules, and environmental sensors. It is also identified as a rooftop relaxation or rest yard in the building plan layout, indicating both utility and planned occupant use [Data: Entities (1755, 655, 643, 657); Relationships (2464, 867, 868, 869)].\\n\\nThis combination of mechanical, energy, and site-use functions makes the rooftop one of the most technically significant areas in the community. The presence of equipment schedules and roof-level equipment numbering shows that rooftop systems are integral to the building’s mechanical design and must be coordinated with other project documentation [Data: Entities (1755, 681, 655, 643); Relationships (907, 867)].\"},{\"summary\":\"Accessibility and door safety requirements are explicitly embedded\",\"explanation\":\"The records include accessibility and safety requirements for doors, including braille signage for visually impaired users, acceptable handle types and mounting heights, and finger-pinch prevention materials required on all doors. The door-related rules are tied to entry doors and are clearly intended to improve usability and reduce hazards [Data: Entities (1339, 1446, 1418, 1419, 1420, 1338, 1445); Relationships (1902, 1901, 1940, 1941, 1900)].\\n\\nThese requirements show that the documentation addresses both regulatory accessibility expectations and everyday safety design. Rather than treating accessibility as optional, the community’s notes present it as part of the project’s mandatory installation criteria [Data: Entities (1436, 1446, 1339, 1338); Relationships (1902, 1941)].\"},{\"summary\":\"The project relies on substitution and specification control\",\"explanation\":\"The notes include a requirement to use equivalent or superior products and systems when substitutions are made, indicating that the design documents set a baseline standard that cannot be weakened without justification. This rule appears alongside the design documents and the NOTE field, which together frame product sel